WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.454 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:11.454 --> 00:00:12.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hi.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:14.440 align:middle line:84%
I'm Lisa Garr, host
of Gaia Inspirations.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:16.890 align:middle line:84%
And our topic for this series,
taped at the Celebrate Your

00:00:16.890 --> 00:00:19.000 align:middle line:84%
Life Conference here
in Phoenix, Arizona,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.450 align:middle line:84%
is to explore the
"I am" meaning.

00:00:21.450 --> 00:00:23.600 align:middle line:84%
And so far, the
meaning of "I am"

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:26.212 align:middle line:84%
is very individual
for each person.

00:00:26.212 --> 00:00:27.670 align:middle line:84%
And joining me
today is someone who

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:32.020 align:middle line:84%
understands how our individual
minds work, Joan Borysenko.

00:00:32.020 --> 00:00:36.130 align:middle line:84%
She is a world-renowned expert
in the mind-body connection.

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:38.290 align:middle line:84%
She's a licensed
psychologist with a doctorate

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:41.000 align:middle line:84%
in cell biology from
Harvard Medical School.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.280 align:middle line:84%
And she bridges cutting-edge
science with deep humanity.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:46.400 align:middle line:90%
So great to have you here.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:48.280 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for being with me.

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:50.590 align:middle line:84%
>>JOAN BORYSENKO: You're
so very welcome, Lisa.

00:00:50.590 --> 00:00:51.590 align:middle line:90%
I'm excited.

00:00:51.590 --> 00:00:53.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So I was telling
you this "I am" meaning

00:00:53.590 --> 00:00:56.380 align:middle line:90%
has taken on a life of its own.

00:00:56.380 --> 00:00:58.660 align:middle line:84%
It walks into the room
and takes a presence.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:00.822 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know how
much experience you

00:01:00.822 --> 00:01:02.030 align:middle line:90%
have with the "I am" meaning.

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:04.019 align:middle line:84%
But what is true
for you right now?

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:05.950 align:middle line:84%
What "I am" statement
could you say?

00:01:05.950 --> 00:01:12.070 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: Well, I could say
I am part of the larger "I am,"

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:16.520 align:middle line:84%
that my whole being lives in
that unified field for which we

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:18.550 align:middle line:90%
have so many names.

00:01:18.550 --> 00:01:22.970 align:middle line:84%
But it was what we call
God who said to Moses,

00:01:22.970 --> 00:01:24.870 align:middle line:90%
"I am that I am."

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:31.300 align:middle line:84%
And specifically, I think,
it's a great statement

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:38.740 align:middle line:84%
because we can't personify it.
"I am that I am" is remarkable.

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:40.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It gets us
into present time.

00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:43.710 align:middle line:84%
I noticed as you were talking,
it just sinks the moment right

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:45.770 align:middle line:90%
into present time.

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:48.150 align:middle line:84%
I feel really
present with you when

00:01:48.150 --> 00:01:49.522 align:middle line:90%
you were talking about that.

00:01:49.522 --> 00:01:50.230 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: Yes.

00:01:50.230 --> 00:01:54.450 align:middle line:84%
And I think what's great about
the sense of "I am that I am"

00:01:54.450 --> 00:01:58.350 align:middle line:84%
is for me, it also means
I'm not what I'm not.

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:01.480 align:middle line:84%
I don't have to worry about
who I think I should be,

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.710 align:middle line:84%
that who I am is just right
at this point in time.

00:02:05.710 --> 00:02:08.120 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And I was talking
about the mind-body connection.

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:10.870 align:middle line:84%
And what we just did is we
just synchronized our minds,

00:02:10.870 --> 00:02:13.690 align:middle line:84%
our body with this present
moment in the "I am."

00:02:13.690 --> 00:02:15.660 align:middle line:84%
And you've explored the
mind-body connection

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:19.640 align:middle line:84%
for so long, which
I absolutely love.

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:22.750 align:middle line:84%
So many years ago, we were
convinced that the mind

00:02:22.750 --> 00:02:24.160 align:middle line:90%
was separate from the body.

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:27.450 align:middle line:84%
And you have done an
amazing job in helping us

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:28.990 align:middle line:90%
understand that it is together.

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:31.360 align:middle line:84%
We are one with our
minds and our bodies.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:32.860 align:middle line:84%
Can you talk a
little bit about what

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:35.650 align:middle line:84%
you've discovered over the years
and what that means to you,

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:38.270 align:middle line:84%
being connected with
your mind and your body?

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:43.360 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: Well, first
of all, the word "mind"

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.840 align:middle line:90%
has not been well-defined.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.870 align:middle line:84%
And in recent years, there's
a whole new field called

00:02:48.870 --> 00:02:51.030 align:middle line:90%
"interpersonal neurobiology."

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's been
really popularized

00:02:55.120 --> 00:03:00.140 align:middle line:84%
by this wonderful neuroscientist
and physician from UCLA.

00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:02.280 align:middle line:90%
His name is Dan Siegel.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:05.860 align:middle line:84%
He got a large group of
people from all disciplines

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:09.750 align:middle line:84%
together to actually
define what the mind is.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.670 align:middle line:84%
Because we say "mind" all
the time, and nobody knows,

00:03:12.670 --> 00:03:13.870 align:middle line:90%
what on earth is the mind?

00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:14.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:18.550 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: And they came
up with a really amazing

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:21.710 align:middle line:84%
definition, that
the mind is really

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:26.850 align:middle line:84%
what carries information and
communication across time,

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:31.120 align:middle line:84%
and that it's both
embodied in us--

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.720 align:middle line:84%
and I'll talk in
a moment about how

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:38.600 align:middle line:84%
the mind is embodied throughout
all of our cells and organs.

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:42.280 align:middle line:84%
But it's also embedded
in our environment.

00:03:42.280 --> 00:03:46.630 align:middle line:84%
And so for example, Lisa,
you and I are talking.

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:51.860 align:middle line:84%
And now our mind has made
informational communication.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:54.870 align:middle line:84%
And what I say registers
in you, doesn't it.

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:58.950 align:middle line:84%
If I say something scary,
you'd feel anxiety.

00:03:58.950 --> 00:04:02.940 align:middle line:84%
If I say something funny,
you would have laughter.

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.700 align:middle line:84%
And you would be making,
at a molecular level,

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:06.820 align:middle line:90%
different hormones.

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:07.895 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Empathy.

00:04:07.895 --> 00:04:08.770 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: Empathy.

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:09.550 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:12.250 align:middle line:84%
Because Dan Siegel, in
fact, founded something

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:14.640 align:middle line:90%
called the Mindsight Institute.

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:18.760 align:middle line:84%
And mindsight is not only
the ability to witness

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:22.079 align:middle line:84%
what's going on in your
own body-mind system

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.920 align:middle line:84%
but to actually tune in
empathetically what's

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.290 align:middle line:90%
going on with another person.

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:32.350 align:middle line:84%
And that leads to a
very beautiful form

00:04:32.350 --> 00:04:33.970 align:middle line:90%
of compassionate communication.

00:04:33.970 --> 00:04:36.530 align:middle line:90%


00:04:36.530 --> 00:04:38.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the mind
is located, of course,

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:39.930 align:middle line:90%
outside the brain, right?

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:41.054 align:middle line:90%
It's located all around us.

00:04:41.054 --> 00:04:43.520 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: It's all
around throughout the body.

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:47.340 align:middle line:84%
And my belief is that
there's a unified field

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:52.890 align:middle line:84%
of intelligence to which we're
all hooking in, a larger mind.

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:54.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So extends
outside of our body--

00:04:54.710 --> 00:04:55.080 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: Yes.

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:55.450 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --into the universe.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:56.324 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: Exactly.

00:04:56.324 --> 00:05:00.060 align:middle line:84%
And there's a fair
amount of experimentation

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:02.450 align:middle line:90%
that shows that's possible.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:04.650 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you
remember the physician

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:09.370 align:middle line:84%
Larry Dossey's work talked about
the three eras of medicine.

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:13.910 align:middle line:84%
The first era, or period
of time, of medicine

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:15.940 align:middle line:90%
being entirely physical.

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:20.550 align:middle line:84%
The second era really looking
at the mind-body connection.

00:05:20.550 --> 00:05:24.380 align:middle line:84%
And the third looking at
this unified quantum field

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:28.800 align:middle line:84%
so that, while I know that
my mind affects my body,

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.610 align:middle line:84%
Larry's Era III is the same
as interpersonal neurobiology

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:37.590 align:middle line:84%
because it says your mind
affects my body and not only

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:40.340 align:middle line:84%
as we sit here
but at a distance.

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:44.790 align:middle line:84%
So that would mean that
distant healing and prayer

00:05:44.790 --> 00:05:51.430 align:middle line:84%
have an effect extending
beyond our body.

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:52.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Which is
amazing because you

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:55.250 align:middle line:84%
started talking about
this 20, 30 years ago

00:05:55.250 --> 00:05:57.670 align:middle line:84%
and did studies at
Duke University then.

00:05:57.670 --> 00:06:01.040 align:middle line:84%
And we're just starting to get
this into our culture, which

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:03.970 align:middle line:90%
is-- it's brilliant.

00:06:03.970 --> 00:06:07.600 align:middle line:84%
And you mentioned-- so let's
talk about the mind traveling

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:09.112 align:middle line:90%
through the body--

00:06:09.112 --> 00:06:09.820 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: Yes.

00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:11.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --on a molecular level.

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:13.390 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: I think
one of the pioneers

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:17.730 align:middle line:84%
in that was my very dear
friend, the late Candace Pert.

00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:22.170 align:middle line:84%
And she was the co-discoverer
of the receptors in our brain

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:26.230 align:middle line:84%
for endorphins, that we
make our own endogenous--

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:29.180 align:middle line:84%
that means "made within
us"-- endorphins.

00:06:29.180 --> 00:06:32.720 align:middle line:84%
And that's why opiates
work, because we

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.700 align:middle line:90%
have an opiate system.

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:39.050 align:middle line:84%
And she discovered, in
general, that every time we

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:41.780 align:middle line:84%
have an emotion, it
releases what she

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:44.230 align:middle line:90%
called "molecules of emotion."

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:48.310 align:middle line:84%
And these little molecules
are tiny little neuropeptides.

00:06:48.310 --> 00:06:51.010 align:middle line:84%
They go through the
blood-brain barrier.

00:06:51.010 --> 00:06:54.750 align:middle line:84%
And they bind to receptor
sites on all of our cells

00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:56.510 align:middle line:90%
like a lock and key.

00:06:56.510 --> 00:06:58.790 align:middle line:84%
So you have a thought,
you have an emotion,

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:02.110 align:middle line:84%
and literally milliseconds
later, your cells all

00:07:02.110 --> 00:07:03.350 align:middle line:90%
get the message.

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:06.280 align:middle line:84%
When the lock and the
key come together,

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:11.080 align:middle line:84%
you have a chemical change
in the nucleus of your cells.

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:15.770 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is that
your genes are either--

00:07:15.770 --> 00:07:18.880 align:middle line:84%
certain genes,
activated or repressed.

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:20.500 align:middle line:90%
And that's an amazing thing.

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:25.220 align:middle line:84%
So your whole body changes
due to your emotions.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.990 align:middle line:84%
This is a field now
called epigenetics.

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:34.400 align:middle line:84%
And we know your DNA does
not just regulate your life.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:38.700 align:middle line:84%
It itself is regulated
by environmental effects.

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.630 align:middle line:84%
And the one that
we're talking about

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:45.040 align:middle line:84%
is the environmental effect of
your own emotions on your DNA.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:48.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Your own thoughts can
turn on, turn off those genes.

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:51.980 align:middle line:84%
And it's so vitally important
what our thoughts are.

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And as Dr. Bruce Lipton
says, our perception

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:56.660 align:middle line:90%
of those thoughts.

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:58.290 align:middle line:90%
That's another level.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:00.630 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I so appreciate that.

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.310 align:middle line:84%
So do you think
that we can turn on

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:07.700 align:middle line:84%
and turn off things like
metabolism with our thoughts?

00:08:07.700 --> 00:08:09.922 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: That's a
really interesting question.

00:08:09.922 --> 00:08:11.338 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I was
thinking about this.

00:08:11.338 --> 00:08:12.970 align:middle line:90%
I'd love to know.

00:08:12.970 --> 00:08:15.710 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: Because
I'm a scientist,

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:17.530 align:middle line:84%
of course I would
say we would have

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:21.010 align:middle line:90%
to do an experiment about that.

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:25.590 align:middle line:84%
But I do know that what you
eat, the food that you eat,

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:28.520 align:middle line:84%
definitely changes
your genetics.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:31.840 align:middle line:84%
There's a tremendous
epigenetic effect of food.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:37.409 align:middle line:84%
So that will definitely help
to regulate your metabolism.

00:08:37.409 --> 00:08:41.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Your latest work
is about the PlantPlus Diet

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:41.909 align:middle line:90%
Solution.

00:08:41.909 --> 00:08:44.724 align:middle line:84%
This is not a
one-size-fits-all diet.

00:08:44.724 --> 00:08:45.390 align:middle line:90%
>>BORYSENKO: No.

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:47.680 align:middle line:84%
And it's not a vegan
solution unless you

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:49.350 align:middle line:90%
happen to be a vegan.

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:53.870 align:middle line:84%
But in a nutshell,
what happened was

00:08:53.870 --> 00:08:58.540 align:middle line:84%
that my beloved
husband found out

00:08:58.540 --> 00:09:01.110 align:middle line:90%
he had calcium in his arteries.

00:09:01.110 --> 00:09:04.310 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, uh-oh,
plaque in the arteries,

00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:07.720 align:middle line:84%
but I know what to do
about that, so I thought.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:10.010 align:middle line:84%
Because there had
been some research

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:15.090 align:middle line:84%
that a very low-fat diet,
ultra low-fat vegan diet,

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:16.630 align:middle line:90%
could reverse that.

00:09:16.630 --> 00:09:20.080 align:middle line:84%
So we went on an ultra
low-fat vegan diet.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:22.170 align:middle line:84%
And like so many
people on a diet,

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:24.530 align:middle line:84%
we were like religious
fundamentalists.

00:09:24.530 --> 00:09:26.800 align:middle line:90%
Everybody should eat this diet.

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:28.500 align:middle line:90%
It'll be so good for you.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:29.730 align:middle line:90%
You'll lose weight.

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:31.570 align:middle line:84%
All these good
things will happen.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:32.840 align:middle line:90%
It's good for the planet.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.230 align:middle line:90%
It's-- you know.

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:38.820 align:middle line:84%
And a year later, his blood
lipids had gone south.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:41.530 align:middle line:84%
They were much worse
than they were before.

00:09:41.530 --> 00:09:45.460 align:middle line:84%
And we both gained
about 10 pounds.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:49.020 align:middle line:84%
So I thought, what
is wrong with this,

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:53.790 align:middle line:84%
because that diet probably saved
the life of President Clinton.

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:54.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:57.910 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: And it works
very well for many people.

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:00.440 align:middle line:90%
But it did not work for us.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:02.900 align:middle line:90%
So I started to scratch my head.

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:05.660 align:middle line:84%
And because I'm
trained as a scientist,

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:10.330 align:middle line:84%
I thought, well, let me go to
the nutrition research, which

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:11.800 align:middle line:90%
I did for three years.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:15.880 align:middle line:84%
And let me tell you, it's the
worst research in the world.

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:17.160 align:middle line:90%
You cannot trust it.

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:20.880 align:middle line:84%
Most of the studies are
what we call retrospective.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:24.605 align:middle line:84%
So instead of saying, OK,
Lisa, change your diet,

00:10:24.605 --> 00:10:29.010 align:middle line:84%
and for 30 years we'll watch
your diet versus someone

00:10:29.010 --> 00:10:33.500 align:middle line:84%
else's-- that's too
difficult to do, generally.

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:36.860 align:middle line:84%
So they do things like ask
people what they've eaten

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:39.230 align:middle line:90%
and then make correlations.

00:10:39.230 --> 00:10:43.600 align:middle line:84%
And you can say something
may be correlated,

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:46.330 align:middle line:84%
but you can't say that one
thing causes the other.

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:48.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because every
body is different.

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:50.450 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: Not only
is every body different,

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:55.140 align:middle line:84%
but it's like saying,
every time you see a fire,

00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:58.110 align:middle line:84%
there are firemen there,
and coming to the conclusion

00:10:58.110 --> 00:11:00.130 align:middle line:90%
that firemen cause fires.

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:03.580 align:middle line:90%
So it's completely erroneous.

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:08.200 align:middle line:84%
A correlation does not
imply actual causation.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:12.040 align:middle line:84%
And I looked at it, and I
said, I cannot believe that

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:15.200 align:middle line:84%
the government has made
dietary recommendations.

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:19.040 align:middle line:84%
And as I looked at studies,
I found almost no good ones.

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:22.700 align:middle line:84%
And as I began to look
through things, I thought,

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:27.230 align:middle line:84%
the American diet
has gone so far

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:32.100 align:middle line:84%
toward refined foods,
particularly refined carbs.

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:34.860 align:middle line:84%
Turns out if you
eat a lot of carbs,

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:39.660 align:middle line:84%
whether they're refined or
whether they're whole grains

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:42.630 align:middle line:84%
that are ground up,
which is still refined,

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:48.090 align:middle line:84%
many people cannot deal with
that amount of carbohydrate.

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And the fact is carbs
eventually turn into fat,

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:54.250 align:middle line:84%
and that's why we got fat, and
that's why my husband's blood

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:56.060 align:middle line:90%
fat was rising.

00:11:56.060 --> 00:11:58.220 align:middle line:84%
Because we're
genetically different.

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:01.730 align:middle line:84%
For example, most people can
eat all the fat they want.

00:12:01.730 --> 00:12:03.767 align:middle line:84%
It does not turn
into cholesterol.

00:12:03.767 --> 00:12:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:12:04.350 --> 00:12:06.710 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: But others
can't do that because they

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:10.940 align:middle line:84%
have multiple copies
of a gene called APOE4.

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:15.520 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out, most
people in this country

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:17.340 align:middle line:90%
are carb-resistant.

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:21.960 align:middle line:84%
And this is why we have, in
part-- there are many reasons--

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:26.890 align:middle line:84%
but in part, why there's an
obesity epidemic and why--

00:12:26.890 --> 00:12:28.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What does
carb-resistant mean?

00:12:28.610 --> 00:12:30.400 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: Well,
that really means

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:33.320 align:middle line:84%
that you can't eat many
carbs because they just

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:34.186 align:middle line:90%
turn into fat.

00:12:34.186 --> 00:12:35.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They don't absorb--

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:36.250 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: They
don't metabolize them

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:37.730 align:middle line:90%
in the same way as other people.

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:39.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: They don't turn
into energy in the body?

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.163 align:middle line:84%
>>BORYSENKO: They
do turn into energy,

00:12:41.163 --> 00:12:43.290 align:middle line:84%
but you only need
so much energy.

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:47.110 align:middle line:90%
And the rest will turn into fat.

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:51.616 align:middle line:90%
But here's the problem.

00:12:51.616 --> 00:12:55.500 align:middle line:84%
If you eat too
many carbs, insulin

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:58.660 align:middle line:84%
can't get into your
cells fast enough,

00:12:58.660 --> 00:13:01.700 align:middle line:84%
and you end up with
high blood sugar.

00:13:01.700 --> 00:13:04.300 align:middle line:84%
And that accumulates
into a product

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:08.930 align:middle line:84%
called advanced glycation end
products-- glycation, glucose.

00:13:08.930 --> 00:13:12.750 align:middle line:90%
So it's a metabolic sludge.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:15.540 align:middle line:84%
And there's no way to
get it out of the body.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:22.430 align:middle line:84%
We have no natural mechanism to
relieve us of these molecules.

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:25.900 align:middle line:84%
And they can eventually
lead to heart failure

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:30.880 align:middle line:84%
and to inflammation and
to a variety of problems.

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:35.900 align:middle line:84%
And so what we know is different
people need different diets.

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:40.460 align:middle line:84%
Some people would do great
on a high carb vegan diet.

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:43.500 align:middle line:84%
Other people, like me,
will grow sick on it.

